text.tspan: Imagine you are a hungry caterpillar.
You want to eat the leaf in front of you,
but you must move closer.
You move your first leg (front left) up,
you move your second leg (front right) backward,
you move your third leg forward,
you move your twelfth leg down.
Now, imagine you have access to a higher level language.
One that allows you to coordinate many legs at once.
The words in this language are;
move forwards, move backwards, turn left, turn right
Now reaching the leaf is as simple as:
Move forwards.
Questions
- How can an agent (efficiently) learn an abstract action space (aka a language)
for (efficiently) describing what they want?
- If an agent has access to an abstract action space (with certian properties),
what advantage might it provide?
(potentially) Useful properties of abstract action spaces
- Disentangled (different actions effect the state independently)
- Regular (an action changes the state in a regular/consistent way)
- Composable (actions can be composed into valid sequences)
- Efficient/Simple (require few actions for typical tasks)
- Expressive (all/most states are reachable)
